This humanitarian project is proposing to both assist the population with emergency intervention in acute nutrition crisis and address consequences of nutrition crisis in areas identified by the consortium where a multi-year approach could improve the nutrition and health status of under 5 children and pregnant and lactating women
ACF response in Cholera outbreak in Kemo (CAR)

ACF started to intervene 5 days after the first joint assessment distributing WASH kits to ensure the access to drinking water and capacities to contain it, sensitization have been made to ensure hygiene promotion. Active screenings were carried out referencing MAS cases in OTP/ ITFC (every 2 weeks) and follow-up is done through home visit when necessary. During the follow-up, the Mental Health & Care Practices (MHCP) is associated (workshop of entrance / workshop of exit / session of relaxation).

A continuation of SHARP (a previous programme under the BRCiS Consortium) 

BRCiS contributes to the resilience pillar but also to the human rights, agriculture, livestock and fisheries, economic development and the Social and Human Development pillars. The Consortium commits to align to the National Development Plan’s vision and goals and to actively coordinate with the relevant Federal Institutions when there are targeted actions that will build community capacity to achieve these goals

Action Against Hunger is pleased to sign this call of interest for EAP Custodian Process in Zimbabwe alongside its local partner, Nutrition Action Zimbabwe, a registered Private Voluntary Organization (PVO 38/19) working in Zimbabwe, which aims to meet the immediate and long-termfood and nutrition needs of targeted communities and building their resilience to respond to repeated shocks.

Action Against Hunger and local partners will evaluate the integration of WaterScope’s bacterial testing system for drinking water into ongoing programmes in Ethiopia and Kenya to improve decision-making on water supply.

Action Against Hunger will directly implement a multi-sectorial response to the flood-affected communities in Helmand province. The ERM team have already provided timely response to vulnerable communities identified in Lashkar Gah, Nawa and Nahr-e-Saraj districts. However, ERM's modus operandi is very specific (strict criteria as regards IDPs) and Action Against Hunger's project, funded by Start, will enable holistic assistance to flood-affected people as a whole (IDPs that ERM is not in capacity to assist and non-IDPs that don't fall into ERM's criteria). As per Action Against Hunger's and other partners' assessment findings, the following activities are proposed: water provision for drinking and other daily use through boreholes rehabilitation, distribution of hygiene kits, hygiene promotion at community level, multipurpose cash, distribution of NFI kits and shelter rehabiliation. Action Against Hunger plans to intervene in the same areas where activities are currently implemented through ongoing projects but currently there are needs and gaps. Outputs: 1. 200 HHs living in rehabilitated shelters 2. 200 of the HHs reporting that they have received NFI kits 3. 7350 people in the targeted areas reporting that they have access to clean drinking water 4. 300 HHs reporting that they received culturally appropriate hygiene kits together with hygiene messages 5. Number of HHs reporting that their needs of health, emergency and transportation are met.

AAH will initiate activities in Odessa and Mykolaiv in order to gradually expand programmatic reach in the South while building on existing work in the East, in particular around Kharkiv. The strategy for Odessa and Mykolaiv will be to utilise AAH Spain’s presence in Moldova and existing partnerships and logistical capacity. In the initial months, AAH Spain will conduct cross-border operations through its partners in Moldova and Odessa. AAH Spain and AAH France have planned a joint assessment in October (security permitting) to kick-start interventions, update understanding of the needs, strengthen partner relationships in Odessa, and prepare for a longer-term presence.
